Trends of Twitch API data¶

Goal: help product manager better understanding of:¶

  • which application developers are important to the developer ecosystem
  • which API endpoints are more important to continue to maintain

Dataset Description¶

Jan 2018

  1. daily_logs.csv – contains the daily API call logs for different applications calling the Twitch API:

    • the_date: the date of the Twitch API
    • client_id: the internal id of a given application calling the Twitch API
    • api_endpoint: the name of a specific Twitch API call, see notes on api_endpoint in the next section for important information about this field
    • num_requests: the total number of times the API call was requested by an application
    • avg_latency: the average latency (in milliseconds) of the API call(smaller latency time, faster getting in API)

  2. app_metadata.csv – contains a mapping of client_id to human readable application names:

    • client_id: the internal id of a given application calling the Twitch API
    • application_name: the name of the application chosen by the application developer
    • application_author: the name of the application developer

The structure of an api_endpoint is the following: {http_request_method} /{twitch_api_version}/{api_endpoint_method} Examples of http_request_method will include GET, POST, PUT, DELETE.

Examples of twitch_api_version include /v3, /v5, and /helix. Note that v3 and v5 versions are old versions of the API, and will be removed on Dec 2018. Helix is the codename of the new Twitch API. Note that different API versions can have the same API endpoint method name.

Examples of api_endpoint_method are numerous, but at a high level they allow the developerto do things like “get metadata on a specific video clip” or “get a list of who is following streamer X”.

Initial Analysis¶

Since we want to find the important developer and API endpoint, we first need to define important. According to available data, there are two metrics(num_requests/avg_latency) we can use to measure how importance one application is.

  • num_requests: shows how popular one application is. The larger number of requests is, the more important the application(endpoint) is. Or if an application shows rapid increase in num_requests, it also indicates this application is increasingly important
  • avg_latency: show how fast clients get response, it measures how well the system is. Larger latency would increase frustration and negative feedback from clients, we want applications with smaller latency time. That is, applications with larger num_requests and smaller avg_latency preform better and are what we desire, thus the developer owns those applications are more important to the developer ecosystem.

For important API endpoints, we also assume popular endpoints(most frequently used & showing increasing trends) are more important, because those API are core products of our company. Especially those popular endpoints with longer latency time, are deserved more effort to maintain and improve. Besides, endpoints with continuous use in the future are more important than those with soonly removement.

Sum up, we need to find developers with most frequently used and less latency applications and popular endpoints with relatively longer latency time, will be continuous use in the future.

There are several values should be noticed in endpoint_types.

  • NaN and ' '. NaN means there are no endpoint_types after API_version, api_endpoint is like GET /v3, while ' ' means after API_version there is blank, like GET /v3/. Both offers no information about endpoint_types. So combine these two value as NaN
  • channels and channel, users and user: No obvious pattern before channels/channel and users/user, which means they might neither related to API_version nor request_method. By roughly check, I find usually channels is followed by end_points most time, and seldom by NaN, while channel is always followed by NaN. Later carefully check.
  • according to the note, the combination of request_method and endpoint_types might represent what developer do, thus might help us find the important endpoints.

#plot_bar function
def get_bar_plot(xlabel, df):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (12,6))
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
    title = "Distribution of " + xlabel
    plt.title(title, fontsize = 18)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel, fontsize = 15)
    plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize = 15)
    vc = df[xlabel].value_counts(dropna = False)
    vcsum = vc.sum()
    vc.plot(kind = 'bar', ax = ax)
    plt.xticks(fontsize=15)
    plt.yticks(fontsize = 15)
    for i,v in vc.reset_index().iterrows():
        ax.text(i,v[xlabel]+1, v[xlabel],ha='left', va='bottom', fontsize = 12)
        ax.text(i,(v[xlabel]/vcsum).round(3) + 1, (v[xlabel]/vcsum).round(3),ha='center', va='top', fontsize = 14)

def get_group_plot(v1, agg_v, df):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (12,6))
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
    gb = df.groupby(['the_date',v1])[v1].agg(agg_v).unstack()
    gb.plot(kind = 'line', ax = ax, width = 0.9)
    plt.title('Trend of ' + v1, fontsize = 18)
    plt.xlabel('The_date', fontsize = 15)
    plt.xticks(rotation = 'vertical')
    plt.ylabel('count', fontsize = 15)
    plt.xticks(fontsize = 14)
    plt.yticks(fontsize = 14)
    plt.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5), fontsize = 13)
    print(df.groupby(['the_date',v1])[v1].agg(agg_v).head(10))

def get_two_group_plot(v1, v2, kind, agg_v, df):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (12,6))
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
    gb = df.groupby([v1, v2])[v2].agg(agg_v)
    gb.plot(kind = kind, ax = ax, width = 1)
    plt.title('Distribution of ' + v1 +" and "+ v2, fontsize = 18)
    plt.xlabel(v1 + "+" + v2, fontsize = 15)
    plt.xticks(rotation = 'vertical')
    plt.ylabel('count', fontsize = 15)
    plt.xticks(fontsize = 14)
    plt.yticks(fontsize = 14)
    #plt.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5), fontsize = 12)
    print(df.groupby([v1, v2])[v2].agg(agg_v))

def get_three_group_plot(v1, v2,v3, kind, agg_v, df):

Summary of Time related(Trend) Analysis¶

As shown above, although with relatively large or small fluctuation, most variables kept the same trend during the last 3 months, with several variables slightly increase/decrease. Next, check the relationship between metrics and variables

3.3 Relationship between variables and num_request/avg_latency¶

how request_method/api_version/endpoint_types/application_author related to num_request/avg_latency quantitively?

One-to-One Relation¶

NOTE:I want to show counts, the num_requests and avg_latency with variables, but they are not in the same quantity. We can normalized the groupby results, so that both can shown in one figure, give us better comparison.

In [294]:
'''
#get plot between num_request and avg_latency with variables
def get_one_group_plot(v1, kind, agg_v, df):

    ssn = df.groupby(v1)[['num_requests', 'avg_latency']].mean().sum()
    gb = df.groupby(v1)[['num_requests', 'avg_latency']].agg(agg_v)/ssn
    ax = gb.plot(kind = kind)
    plt.title('Relationship between ' + v1 +' and num_requests/avg_latency')
    plt.xlabel(v1)
    plt.xticks(rotation = 'vertical')
    plt.ylabel(agg_v + ' of num_requests/avg_latency(%)')
    plt.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5))
    print(gb)
 
'''
In [208]:
#combine num_requests/avg_latency/counts into one figure
def get_one_group_plot(v1, kind, agg_v, df):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (12,6))
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
    ssn = df.groupby(v1)[['num_requests', 'avg_latency']].mean().sum()
    gb = df.groupby(v1)[['num_requests', 'avg_latency']].agg(agg_v)/ssn
    count = df[v1].value_counts()/df[v1].value_counts().sum()
    gb['count'] = count
    gb.plot(kind = kind, ax = ax, width = 0.9)
    plt.title('Relationship between ' + v1 +' and num_requests/avg_latency', fontsize = 18)
    plt.xlabel(v1, fontsize = 16)
    plt.xticks(fontsize = 16, rotation = 'vertical')
    plt.yticks(fontsize = 15)
    plt.ylabel(agg_v + '/count of num_requests/avg_latency(%)', fontsize = 15)
    plt.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5), fontsize = 15)
    print(gb)

One to two relationship¶

Since groupby 2 or more variables, there are many the combinations, show the results in one figure might be not clear enough, so I redo seperately plot the relationship of num_requests/ avg_latency and other variables

In [223]:
#ONE# same as get_one, normalize the results, so that both can be shown in one figure
def get_multiple_group_plot(v1, v2, kind, agg_v, df):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (12,6))
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
    ssn = df.groupby([v1, v2])[['num_requests', 'avg_latency']].mean().sum()
    gb = (df.groupby([v1, v2])[['num_requests', 'avg_latency']].agg(agg_v)/ssn)
    gb.plot(kind = kind, ax = ax, width = 0.9)
    plt.title('Relationship of num_requests/avg_latency with ' + v1 +' and '+ v2, fontsize = 18)
    plt.xlabel(v1 + '+' + v2, fontsize = 15)
    plt.xticks(rotation = 'vertical', fontsize = 15)
    plt.ylabel(agg_v +' of num_requests/avg_latency (%)', fontsize = 15)
    plt.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.5), fontsize = 15)
    print(gb)
